At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange bounced in the negative
After Tuesday morning’s fall, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, at the start of trade, the Prague stock exchange resumed its fall the day before, when it lost nearly six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The market's reaction to the outcome of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilization plan, is thus also perceptible in our country.
Declining shares in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices managed, over the course of the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trade, but later wiped out part of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange were losing more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“Hesitation about the US bailout will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong’s monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries would be at risk of being affected.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion K<0xC4><0x8D>).
The lawmakers thus denied the call for support for President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday and major stock indices experienced the biggest decline in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a fall of such magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress Gives Up: U.S. Government Can Inject $700 Billion in Banks
U.S. Congressional leaders and President George W. Bush’s government have agreed on a broader form of the financial assistance agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turning point in the talks on adopting a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
Success, however, is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and submit it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to a vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout plan will be adopted should be the first major psychological factor to revive financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences of opinion about the form the package of measures should take to stabilize the market," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On Saturday-Sunday night, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It should buy back from financial corporations the unselling real estate assets that cause significant losses to financial corporations and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be pursued, but I think we are there," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian exchanges
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on falling stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are making sure Congress reaches a definitive agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before the start of trades in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the Congressional decision could affect trades on Monday.
At the moment, however, it is impossible to say for sure when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote, or if the negotiations are not likely to be blocked at the last moment by this or that problem.
Legislators hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nonetheless, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system shall be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, should be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option of blocking the granting of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomed the progress in the negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the opportunity to veto it in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which consisted of obtaining finance for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to pass the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated “the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said the legislators agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the settlement of deductions, the development of the plan on the timeline.
The new Act also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for real estate owners, who are having trouble paying.
The government should negotiate new deposits in the case of mortgages it is going to buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological help
According to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“And that’s because we don’t know what the mechanism and the price of buying back troubled assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, according to Marek, is not as important as that.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree, starting this week, that they support this plan and that they dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, foreseen for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time," Marek said.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you on how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear from this that it is better to buy only a phone.
There is no doubt that there are enough reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy a high-end expensive gramophone for the house to put on the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on vinyl, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason, for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you are at least likely dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same goes for music on the move, i.e. compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3.
Also, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it can be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time carrying headphones bought for twenty crowns on the market.
There are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobiles.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and sending SMS, it is able to play music and movies, record the latter, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even serve for navigation.
And if we take into account Smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal nature of mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between two reloads.
And playing music is one of the most important energy goinfres.
Mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours are rare, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, the music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) are significantly more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count on them to play music only for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second charge for work - this being true even for more expensive devices.
There will be no problem for MP3 players, which are able, following a reload, to run continuously for at least 9 hours, including the less powerful ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile device.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
When it comes to drives, you don't need, except (iPod), any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device coming from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a media library sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or the user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, you are mainly interested in the life of the battery, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example, taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Virtually all mobile devices are capable of this.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
Everyone gets to play MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will come up to you will have just this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
All you need to do is visit the corresponding web pages of the operator (or of another provider) from your mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical mobile.
The operator's offer is unfortunately miserable and is, in most cases, limited to quick-made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile phones with them.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of mobile music is its price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can already have a very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best-equipped, also equipped with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
The readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy control.
Really anyone manages to secure the order of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a tape station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models generally support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones even get through with 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you must not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman phones (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman phones have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the farthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no longer room for another operator, makes a chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with his or her own network is apparently no longer very lucky (by the way, now it would be hard to find frequencies).
Now, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which, subsequently, conventional operators must also react.
Yet, even before the introduction of party-turners such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard today in our country were being heard in Britain.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We don’t have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order for them to operate efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity hit.
In fact, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work for us too.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, spokesman for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very proactive.
Mobilking will instead be launched in other countries in our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not, for a long time, concealed its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to move forward in the negotiations," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Perhaps the future is promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At the moment, we don’t think there’s room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to others.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not recorded at the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
“It is virtually impossible for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Instead, Vodafone focuses its attention on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our opinion, means the most contributions from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore a decrease in their profits.
So what is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to understand each other like thieves in the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
Nowadays, the U:fon is ready to serve as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented on this: "The competition in the mobile market has recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, this is not only the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter took its typical position in the face of this problem.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the potential stakeholders' offer has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS said in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not be surprising on the part of representatives of operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile phone services."
Pressuring towards a fair functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x93>OHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all gas stations is probably due to the chance and the fierce fight of the competition.
"The Office has not detected any signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither of the operators has a dominant position, and consequently neither has an increased corresponding responsibility for their market behaviour.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even for the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market constitutes one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator logically has the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are apparently proceeding in a similar manner.
Nevertheless, the complaints of many interested parties (including the already mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Reclaiming responsibility for the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common practice in communications, whereby the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act, an extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not succeeded, although many specialists have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one is looking, it can work
That said, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Personalized mobile phone services are offered for example by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic trick is that the company in front of the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you are referring to happened, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would review and that could lead to a termination of collaboration with the company in question," Kemrová said.
Nonetheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not reached even the heads of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is opposed to such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible profits, and at the same time, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot dispose of it fully, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
Now, that is precisely what should seem strange to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, there is another question to the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively wide powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a considerable reduction in the price of services.
Now, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, the conventional operators were striving, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are treating this issue in the way of a hot potato from which one gets rid by transmitting it to a nearby target.
As a result of the experience we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable to them in these cases.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the beating.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our house, the Czech mobile market may get back in motion.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Ji<0xC5><0x99>í B<0xC4><0x9B>lohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, a choir performance and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kate<0xC5><0x99>ina Kn<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0xBE>ínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Kr<0xC4><0x8D>ek are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the server iHNed.cz.
B<0xC4><0x9B>lohlávek considers the Czech national anthem as one of the most beautiful anthems.
As he had previously entrusted to <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
