Sudanese Demand Referendum in the US
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans demanded that <0xC5><0xA0>umava be incorporated into the United States.
This is the result of a letter deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna.
Germans from <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> Krumlov prayed in the letter to the US president not to allow "<0xC5><0xA0>umavská <0xC5><0xBE>upa" (forest region in southern Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation well and we want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter, signed, reads.
Given that the rallies with Czechoslovakia are supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, ruthless attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to always take into his hands the protectorate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava now.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state alien to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has contributed in no way to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of <0xC5><0xA0>umava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of the post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sudeten period.
While the Czech Germans had to at least anticipate that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some were expecting the United States and Britain to gain some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German from <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein region's capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to learn Czech.
"They believed that once they got home, the Czech would be profitable to them," says Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war estimated, according to him, that, following the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
