In exchange for peace, Olmert would return almost all the occupied territories.
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli interim government, advocated the restitution of virtually all occupied territories in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made this statement in an interview published Monday by the Yedioth Ahronoth newspaper.
“We need to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all,” Olmert told the daily.
“We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to give the Palestinians a similar percentage (of the Israeli territory), since without it, peace will not be made,” he added.
He admits that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
“He who desires security in Jerusalem, and above all does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as has happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem,” Olmert said, referring to the two attacks in the city in July.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical places" located inside the Old City.
“Whoever wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It will not work," he later pointed out.
Retreat from the Golan Heights
Olmert also supported Israel's retreat from the Golan Heights, which he believes is a prerequisite for a peace agreement with Syria.
However, this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"I am not proposing to conclude peace with Syria solely on the basis of a Golan retreat," he said.
“The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to renounce their current relations with Iran; they will have to renounce their relationship with Hezbollah (the Shia movement); they will have to renounce the constant support they give to terrorism of Hamas (the Shia movement), Al-Qaeda (the terrorist network), as well as that of the D-jih.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are stewards in the car illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance car is forbidden
In the context of the tragic bus accident of the Student Agency company near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move inside the bus during the journey.
"If the law was to be strictly and formally complied with, the activity of a steward is contrary to the road traffic law," Transport Ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka said.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the bus route.
The girl was sadly sitting next to the driver, in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two more seats at her disposal.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even brake abruptly, even when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the bus is under its technical sheet equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing seats; this has been confirmed at Aktualn<0xC4><0x9B>.cz by the director of the company Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura.
"This is a matter that we have dealt with with the ministry and, at the beginning, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got that passengers can go to the toilet during the journey provided they have their own seat," he said.
The law ignores stewards.
“There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of steward – no legal prescription addresses that role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement also prohibits the carrier from offering services.
The Road Transport Act knows only the term vehicle receiver; it does not define its rights and duties," added spokesman Hanzelka.
Josef Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, the director of the Department of Road Vehicle Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law addresses the issue sufficiently.
"It all depends on whether the bus has in its approval the permission to propose standing seats.
It’s all in there,” he said.
Buses are divided into urban ones, where there are standing places and limited maximum speed, intercity ones with standing places and higher authorized speed and long-distance buses without standing place with the highest authorized maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
As in the airplane, says an expert
Jaroslav Ho<0xC5><0x99>ín, an expert at BESIP (road safety) in transport safety, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of the service in the aircraft.
Nor is it certain when a turbulence will occur and the hostess of the air can shake her head."
"Or, in the event that the bus would have braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
Same as in an urban bus or tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards through internal regulations," he says and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the issue is not resolved.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only bus carrier to offer stewards services.
He hired two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their profession to be a risky profession.
"However, as soon as I have the impression that this is a risky trade, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper on board.
It would also reduce costs,” he said.
The safety concern is the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles the director of Asiana Alexei Litvine, who ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have any hostesses, we've opposed it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end up in a fatal accident," he told T<0xC3><0xBD>den.cz a year ago.
An immense tragedy has come.
A young hostess from the Pilsen region, who had been working for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using flashing and blocked the road to the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid it by means of a sudden maneuver, but he crawled it from his right side.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura refused to sell the two seats reserved for the stewards' rest.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company intends to file a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but in terms of financial compensation, it also relies on the culprit.
A change to the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been in the process of being drafted for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Department of Transportation, could provide clarifications on how stewards travel on board the bus.
"Now, she has not come to any conclusion on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says expert Ho<0xC5><0x99>ín.
"The Ministry of Transportation does not consider the activity of stewards to be fundamentally endangering the safety of passengers," said spokesman Hanzelka, adding that the control of the safety of buses is under the control of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
The hopes of the Dusseldorfers rest on Frankfurt.
The big words were not lacking in the letter addressed by the WestLB Steering Committee to the employees of the house.
Due to a union of the entities of the financial institution of Düsseldorf with the Deka-Bank of Frankfurt, "the central institution of the financial markets of the financial group of the Sparkasse" could be constituted, according to the correspondence made public Monday.
The WestLB would bring a "competence block" doubled with sustainable productivity in such a case.
All in all, such a relationship could be the decisive blow to other concentrations in the banking sector of the Länder.
This is what it looks like when a board of directors wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because the WestLB, injured, is still under heavy pressure.
It is not only the European Commission, but also the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority that, only recently, has made it clear to the Government of the Land of North Rhine-Westphalia that time has been taken into account in the search for a future solution.
For some time now, however, there has been a question - also on the side of Frankfurt - of a relationship of any kind between Deka Bank, which knows the clients of the Sparkasse through their investment funds, and WestLB.
The head of the Deta-Bank, Franz Waas, said at the presentation of the figures for the end of August that he saw no sense in the merger of the Mainzer Landstrasse house with a Land bank, whether Helaba or WestLB.
However, the Board of Directors of the Deka, each half of which is supported by both the Landesbanken and the savings bank groups, instructed the Steering Committee to conduct talks with the WestLB with a view to joint business activities.
It could then be the flow of the financial market, or parts of it.
The talks, however, have only just begun, it is said in the financial square.
This is not the first time Deta-Bank, which, with its 3,000 employees, counts as one of the most important employers on the financial square in Frankfurt, has come into play when it comes to consolidating the savings banks sector.
In 2003 it was believed for a while that the Deta-Bank could merge with the Bank of the Land of Rhineland Palatinate and the Halbab.
However, nothing came out of this ternary bouquet.
The plans had barely been made public that the government of the Land of Hesse was opposed to any participation of the Hellaba in them.
Afterwards, the other two houses did not join either.
The Bank of the Land of Rhineland-Palatinate was attached instead to the Bank of the Land of Baden-Wuttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been new negotiations on the merger of the Deka-Bank with Länder banks.
Lastly, however, Günther Merl, chairman of the Hellaba Steering Committee, had spoken out against any commercial strategy of merger with his bank.
Regardless of this, the feeling seems to be spreading that the reunification of the various public sector institutions is particularly urgent.
Now that the parliamentary elections in Bavaria have passed, a union of the BayernLB with the Bank of the Land of Baden-Wuttenberg could materialize in the first place.
For the Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure for new mergers were to increase, the potential partners were gradually escaping.
In the South, she would now be a junior partner, although she had so far withstood the crisis better than the banks of Munich and Stuttgart.
The Hesse-Thuringia Savings and Transfers Group, which owns 85 per cent of Helaba's capital, locked any union with WestLB earlier this year.
The NordLB would remain strict.
Such geo-strategic reflections, however, reflect only one of the facets.
Another facet is the question of how the different business models of each of these banks can match.
In June, Merl stated that the crucial question, namely, which business model should ensure the future capacity of the Landes banks, had not been solved by the German group of savings and transfers funds.
Eventually, a WestLb debugging could take place, debugging which is obviously not desired here.
This is also what is discussed in the letter of the existing Steering Committee: in any case, a "global solution" for the establishment would be targeted.
How all this will be put in the same basket with the union of certain entities with the Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
