Nights of insomnia for shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician used the word "relatively" and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This was indeed the case this weekend.
The banker of the Bavarian real estate Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, receives from a consortium of German banks a loan of one billion to protect itself from turbulence of the markets.
A person in confidence in the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are issued up to an amount of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>35 billion.
Hypo Real Estate is now expected to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financer had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which has not been possible since the suspicion of markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 per cent to EUR 2.37 million, and the equity rate had also slightly weakened from 1.6 per cent to 1.45 per cent.
Ongoing and net profits from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period last year, with profits from the assignment of defined debts and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit operations falling from more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only thanks to the significant benefits derived from the repayment of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group, as well as the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies that the profit deficit was moderated by about 16 percent.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financer had initially misspeculated on industrial real estate loans, which had subsequently been affiliated with Aareal Bank.
Due to the fact that conventional state funding was not profitable enough, Depfa then engaged more intensively in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private and state investors (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, the Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations that should have on the calculation of the profits and losses of the group an essential material effect that still remains quite vague.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
Already by 2007, they had been truncated to two-thirds.
Hypo Real Estate is, since the acquisition of Depfa, a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing in the interbank market since it does not have any customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has again dwindled considerably, with banks accumulating their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs annually for a portion - about 50 Billion Euros - of the Depfa's total loans of a short-term medium of refinancing.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing need is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of the international financial markets largely out of state currently.
Other sources say that refinancing would be ensured through the funds until the end of 2009.
On the other hand, the Chairman of the Board of Directors of HRE Georg Funke explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to the medium-term financial markets.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority (Bafin) are based on the principle that the market capacity of the Hypo Real Group is now secured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors have to wait.
However, given the dynamics and the imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the bank is, according to the latest statements, still on the doorstep of insolvency on Sunday evening, this at least provisional bailout will not be able to reassure the minds either.
The share price fell from 75 percent to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.30.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While the debts at first have barely moved, the prices of second-rate loans are slipping.
The most affected are the investment funds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and of course those that have a life expectancy beyond 2009.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate Bank previously appeared to be an alternative speculative investment, now their value must be considered as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institution itself that brought the crisis into the institution by the purchase of Depfa Bank.
As long as issuing institutions, governments and less-affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, one can assume a resorption of backlogs over time.
Or what no one dares to hope at the moment will happen – that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed sounds of partial nationalization, the probability that was approaching security has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia primarily for long-term creditors on the decision of whether they should separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line on to constitute a deferment of losses for the next few years on the next automatically deducted equity income tax.
Sylvana and the Secrets of the Box in Bento
When 16-year-old Sylvana Hiltrop has to show up for the first day at Tachibana High School, the girls start laughing: the German is so "kawaii"!
What does that mean? What does it mean?
Sylvana already knows this word thanks to the Mangas - in her new Exchange Log, she speaks of Japan.
"The first day of school in Japan.
What was it that I was excited about?
The road to school was scary for me.
I live on the outskirts of Tokyo towards Kawasaki and take the 40-minute train to Tachibana High School.
I had to find my way alone, thankfully I didn’t get lost.
The beginning of the courses does not seem to be fixed as strictly as with us in Lower Saxony.
The students appear one after the other from eight o'clock, until at nine o'clock less twenty, a round of tables begins with the teacher, the "home room".
But before the class started, it was up to me to introduce myself.
I’m not the kind of person who likes to talk in front of people, especially in front of a class of 40 students.
