At that time, I was very happy to have started learning the language two years ago.
The 31 girls in the class all had low Masses, laughed and made signs, and I constantly heard the word "Kawaii."
I knew him by my mangas.
It belongs to the vocabulary indispensable to the survival of Japanese teenagers and means "cute, cabbage".
Then I quickly slipped into my place.
The girl next to me made me a big ironic smile, she thought it was an honor for the correspondent to sit next to her.
The rest of the hour was pretty quiet, but when the gong resonated, I was assaulted in the rules.
Everyone was talking to who was better, laughing and asking me a lot of questions - in this case, it's hard enough to understand Japanese English.
During the break, they all took out their Bento.
My foster mother had also made me this kind of lunchbox - it's really different than the miserable German snacks.
I had rice with aromatic herbs, small sausages, a cucumber and algae salad, fruits and some sort of meat surrounded by tofu.
Most of the time, I have no idea what I eat exactly here in Japan.
