Rats also have sensations.
A rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without which I or anyone else has so far been able to prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we penetrate hard-to-practice grounds because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
Humans behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective life to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in leadership and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
Therefore, at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity might reside in the linguistic nature of man: much of his existence being related to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internally and subjectively, cannot be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses us with major problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious living, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their contents, and this is exactly what happened during studies on the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does it mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its aftermath, such as the body’s reactions) takes hold of living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluble nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to attribute them to others than ourselves.
On the contrary, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities arise in the regions of the body sensation of the cortex and brain stem, just like Jaak Pankseep, who however focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could quite participate in cross-sectional sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is undemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in humans and in rats is likely to be felt as such in both cases: how could one still check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees from danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my opinion, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Certainly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain stems, while cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brainstem the source of the sensations?
And even if we could prove it to humans, how could we prove it to rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is progress on the nervous plane as the same is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor do I know if sensations exist.
We could judge this as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly hitting myself against a wall.
I am a pragmatic emotional person.
