Talking while sleeping
Some children talk at night.
I do not refer to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk during their sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somnilocchia.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, there are more than one who talks at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence.
They are often linked to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (pissing in bed) or somnambulism, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or overexcitement.
Anyway, this is an unstudied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks with a small quiet voice, with isolated words, murmurs or, on the contrary, with screams, tears, long speeches...
In the event that sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleep talks appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It is useless since he is unconscious and you would wake him up.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he shows himself very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he’s saying (which is not usual), don’t be tempted to question him for information.
You won’t get anything, because sleeping, he’s not conscious to be able to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he is saying, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don’t worry, it’s nothing bad, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
