The Interview - Blood Becomes Safe Again
Héma-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public outcry, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was delayed in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Corporation to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its operations, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and field work in the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," she said, proudly saying that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its inception, on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease were seen in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, measures are put in place.
In April 1999, blood was refused to people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Now, a few years ago, it was undoubtedly demonstrated that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode has thus shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied makes sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid testing (TAN), which allows the presence of the virus itself and not antibodies to the virus, directly in the blood of donors, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs allowed to shorten the silent period, which spans between the moment when the person was infected and the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors may be infected without their knowledge and that they may not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that one can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain health," says the head of Hema-Québec's management.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year appeared on the island of Reunion the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr Décary, noting that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
“The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cell or platelet refills.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
Any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria can still donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-stricken country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Since today’s life is so hectic, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating our blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago the bank-sale of our thousandth cord blood sample and more than a thousand are expected to be taken each year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year,” says Dr. Decary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Multiple mothers are disappointed to not be able to access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
