Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small, unpaid publishing house in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamatory prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the nearly bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will scare the opposition and frighten anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public opinion that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada normally take place through the exchange of ideas and not by punching.
It was therefore sufficient for the mine to open its books, files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust the public and rejects petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while despising the opinions of that same public?
In the world of the Vice-President, it seems that this word only refers to high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers do so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not within the framework of what many perceive as a prosecution-buffalo (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has, moreover, filed a notice at the place of the authors of Black Canada's term of intimacy).
Beyond Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s pursuit is a direct attack on academic research freedom and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of repeated prosecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and Congressional leaders, both Republican and Democrat, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It includes: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, and a right to look at wages paid to managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
“Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing Wall Street crisis,” she said.
"That's the fundamental point: if we don't do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to Americans' daily lives will be immense," Gregg said.
Negotiations had turned to sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a further failure on the investor’s mood would have.
The agreed time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election have been rather favorable to the agreement, but have not failed to express their dissatisfaction that we are forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that aimed at allowing owners to retain their homes and that on the salary of the executives of the companies rescued by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be commended.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on American television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The big lines I’ve read [show] that it’s something that we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option of not doing anything is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem dubious, risky assets from U.S. financial institutions with taxpayers’ money.
It comes after 14 months of a financial crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (subprimes) before expanding to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and bankruptcy.
It was a group of Republicans who overthrew the first draft of the deal last week.
It is believed to have emerged from this deadlock since Democrats accepted that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corner for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government had to bear losses for five years with this program, it could set up new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion, to which another 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion should be approved by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain stakes in the rescued companies that will give him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the torment has passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and severance payments paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The plan's architects would like to see him put to the vote in the House of Representatives as of today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one about taking advantage of taxpayers.”
A small group in Congress called "the caucus of the skeptics," Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully consider the path to take," he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up to acquire its competitor in the midst of shipwreck since it lost <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2 billion (US$2.9 billion) in the U.S. mortgage crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
“This is not lost money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, one recovers a right to vote in the bank and influence.
This is precisely something that savers and households appreciate now that times are uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed about to nationalize another bank damaged by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after the Northern Rock, to be nationalised by the British government since the beginning of this financial crisis.
