What could Zuschlag & amp; Company do in their invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damage; other charges have been brought against them, such as false and the use of false ones.
According to the prosecution, money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand into the boxes of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand, into the pockets of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to get the money from the grants obtained by issuing expense invoices, behind which no actual benefit was provided and thus the associations never met their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the bills were false.
For the latter, they procured invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while making the seals at Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that were to appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the deposition of the latter, he had to spot pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he requested an invoice, on the model of which they would make the other invoices that they would introduce, inter alia, with the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados's choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice established on behalf of the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation, which would later bear the name of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was fraught with flaws in form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could stay overnight, yet the invoice mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
Bill issuers with overflowing imagination also fell into excess when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, which also belongs to the Horeca sector. In their accounting, neither the name of Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért nor that of the Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor.
Gy<0xC5><0x91>z<0xC5><0x91> Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were false documents.
"Our company name and tax number were placed in the wrong place on the seal."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that, according to the invoice, a hundred people stayed there, did not fit either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
Zealous invoice issuers also did not inquire about Budapest travel agencies, being part of their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
Moreover, as was apparent during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while travel benefits, whose destination is outside the European Union, are charged without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up on behalf of the Hotel Révfülöp on the order of Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ert was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, the employees of the hotel issued only invoices to be printed, as soon as the invoices were issued.
The prosecution investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes in referring to the carriage of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was investment advice.
Moreover, it is also for vices of forms, such as inadequate bill types and false seals, that the bills issued on the order of Együtt to Armadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and of Biztos Pont proved to be false.
As in the case of the company Ravenna Bt. or the sports internship in Kunfehértó, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
The counterfeiters also paid no attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at their home.
Invoices Deliberately Established
Another category of invoice issuers is those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal group - Ifjú Szocialisták, has established an invoice for the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the order of the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfeny<0xC5><0x91> association which was not effective in providing the five-millions of Egyesület.
There was no financial movement, either, as the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this was avoided by the agencies in their accounts.
The following category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly related to the accused.
Thus, the administrative delegate of the CEO of the company Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where he was not found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, these equipments were allegedly purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov also reportedly sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the Atlasz, Hoppa and Együtt companies to Armadik Evezredért Alapítvány, and that he pocketed their counter-value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In reality, none of these companies were operating, which the defendant explains by the fact that they were not receiving work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused and editor of the company's founding documents, he established invoices on their behalf, in the order of associations related to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generación.
Kubatov gave organizations, 15 invoices in total, issued by the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecutor thought that 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices as well as the VAT went into Kubatov’s pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to establish fictitious invoices that were used as part of Biztos Pont’s grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generación Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a grant application to the public utility of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They received this subsidy in the amount of twice HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To avoid confusion, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
In fact, these invoices were found during the search carried out in the office of <0xC3><0x81>rpád Kemecsei, at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will report on the method of making the invoices, as they had done before the prosecution.
What might be really interesting would be that the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the slightest detail, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or perhaps the Socialists would have concluded an agreement under which in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the fifty million HUF, Zusi would wear the hat alone.
Today, the latter is probably vexed, since applications for his placement in supervised residence, on the basis of a relief from his conditions of detention, continually fall into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much more damage, and the perpetrators of economic crimes that cannot be repaired, are walking freely or at least, they are waiting at their own home for the end of the procedure.
The Psychology of Over-Auctioning: Why Do We Spend More Money?
When auctioning, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans do not want to be distanced from this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay a price too high.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain areas of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the over-auction of a third party, the whole under the brain stem, called the striatum, moved intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-stimulation" mechanism.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economic members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overpricing a partner under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and so they made their bid.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received him those $15 before the auctions, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was on victory in one group, and failure in the other.
By proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the players' team "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
One hundred miles is estimated to be the number of patients with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles are treated, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B anyway. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become clearer and the urine takes a darker color.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneakyly destroys the cells of the liver. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the organism, thus the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article in which researchers from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing the extent to which belief in God could influence tolerance for human pain.
As part of this at least bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them was observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a palpation technique of the human brain, it was also possible to discover that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university participate.
Specifically, the experiment takes place as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look closely at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady at the Hermitage painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evokes a sort of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, concerned its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and in the meantime, received 20 electroshocks in four parts successively, while looking at either the religious-themed or the more general-themed painting.
The Catholics said that in the view of the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe”, as someone who is “cared for” and they “calmed, and peace has invaded them.”
In view of the religious theme painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided they find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, an Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
“The practice of faith should change and in many cases, it actually changes our personality,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if the believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would a better quality view of the Virgin Mary lead to better results?
