The reason may also be that geeks see very precisely the problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet, and what the Web 2.0, the most promulgated keyword of recent years, pulls right behind it.
Indeed, Web 2.0 concerns nothing but collaboration, but the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the communication channels at our disposal, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young man, in general, can hold a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link these to other services, such as Twinter, or at last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then he can link these to a system of prosecution, such as F-Feeds or Blip.fm.
While we can get acquainted with many private examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands at the sight of the morning photos, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom his unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that dismissed one of his employees, only for the honest opinions that he has written on his blog can be the whole thing of life.
One who lives an online life is made up of what he shows of himself, and this is how one can define the principle behind the behavior of today's young people.
The one who wants to hide something, or at least wants to try to circumvent Google’s monopoly, can do it (beginning, for example, with Scroogle, using Google’s search engine, but at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who, deliberately, do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them, is not the least. Google's online services, from text processing to image processing, to reading information can be replaced by alternative versions having, which are not associated with our profile and are not better served.
