The smart car imitates the bourdon flight
What better method would be to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like the bees, for example.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan’s engineers the strategic start-up idea, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini-robot car, a bio-inspired, BR23C-type self-driving system, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, of oval shape, which in reality, looks a lot like our safe protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the brand's research and development and technological public relations department.
The bee's facet eye plays a major role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the facet eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver is carried out entirely instinctively.
“If it weren’t for this, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for now the collision is considered unavoidable.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process should take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference can not go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the endless combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotational movement, the acceleration as well as the slowing as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentrate is larger, making their lifespan longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, in this way it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of technology for instant avoidance, which Nissan estimates will be introduced to mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles in his way.
