Moreover, the program differs from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which mentioned that the $700 billion had to be spent at once, for the repurchase of securities on dubious credits.
From now on, a maximum of half of the sum of 700 billion can be spent. The first 250 billion will be issued immediately after the adoption of the law by Congress, probably on Monday. This first amount will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy dubious claims from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be disbursed to the President.
The program will be supervised by an independent body, in which the Federal Reserve Chairman will also participate.
Spending the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase dubious debts, dubious mortgage and mortgage securities, as well as other types of "toxic" debts.
Departmental officials said the purchases can take place as part of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to participate in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools of concern, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the necessary tools to devote $700 billion to the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast repurchase of dubious debts, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system leading to the collapse of one or another major financial institution.
"We will take the necessary measures to be ready for the law, as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, bank leaders who are in bad postures and awaiting state aid can expect their starting allowances, simply called off-Atlantic golden parachute, to be capped by the government.
In addition, the limitations depend on the way the Treasury Secretariat offers its assistance to the company.
The ceiling principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys out as part of an auction, they will charge an excess tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Immediately after the repurchase of the dubious debts, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not exaggerated.
In order for the picture to be complete, it is necessary to add that the existing golden parachutes are not changed. The ceiling applies only to new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal limits will be in place on the appointments of CEOs - commented the chairman of the House Financial Benefits Committee, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State acquires a right to acquire shares in the participating banks, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they can even be a winner in the case as soon as the economy and with it the rescued banks fall back on their feet.
The bill mentions that in the next five years, the President must present to Congress a proposal that will decide on how losses will be refunded to taxpayers, starting with the financial sector.
On both sides, there were obviously those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
