Industrial prices have continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent from the previous month, and by 12.9 percent from the month of August 2007, according to the Central Statistics Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to the previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 per cent from the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent from the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors have only experienced a slight increase of about 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear sector (2.8 per cent), with firstly, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of footwear with a 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials have resulted in significant monthly increases in prices in the chemicals and products manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 per cent) and a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase, between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant weight in domestic industrial operations, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the rising gas price set by the authorities since July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, oil processing sector prices experienced the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases occurred in the sectors of textile and textile products production (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the entire processing industry, prices have risen by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors surpassed those of the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
Among domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increases (0.7 per cent) were those that initiated profit on investment.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices have risen by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for subsequent processing have not changed from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent processing (16.8 per cent).
In the sectors of consumer goods production, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, rose by 1.1 percent in August from the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment method weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar; compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
