Mp3 player pointing fingers, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent damage to hearing.
This is what the European Commission is announcing, citing in a statement released in Brussels the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the EU's newly identified unforeseen health risks (Csserri), published today.
"From this scientific report - we read in the note - it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable musical devices, for more than an hour a day and a week, are at risk of permanent hearing loss."
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones may unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” Kuneva said.
“According to scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine the existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow the new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientists-concluded the EU executive-confirm that there is good reason to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents, against similar noise exposure from portable devices and music devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about the hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit this data well by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the limits currently in force regarding the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods risk a permanent loss of hearing after 5 years.
This affects 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at about 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
