In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the phenomena that have been lurking for some time, to the point that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the realisation, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of the sovereign state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions that obviously have close relations with the outside world, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation really seems out of the question or it does not have much to say: the obvious evidence is provided to us by the European Union, which, as usual, shared between the various interests and between the various national strategies, cannot decide on any common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a love of credit: when you go through a difficult period, it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements of which no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the state-nation crisis is, after all, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at one stroke the only thing that our future will have to regulate them.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but that are absolutely related to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign certainly possesses more cards than he who is not, that is, he who is unlucky to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proven inadequate and full of shadow.
And in addition, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even troubling: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of distance that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus increases even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more foreign to the opinions of the majority.
