The super glue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring barely 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep glued a 100 kilogram body on a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that allow to ensure the animal, a perfect adhesion.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the paws of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "easily detaches from the wall," says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
“This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” Liming Dai adds.
Could it be to walk on the walls like Spiderman? Maybe it is, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electrical current.
Other applications could be related to aerospace engineering.
At the moment, no superhero.
The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented a microfiber-like adhesive that self-cleanses dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
