Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market is not in crisis.
According to the latest survey of Sunia, the tenants’ union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin must support - explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the strong demand from the general process of deforming the market has so much
In most cases, rental offers also include a number of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, no rental limit, sub-rentals.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the tax, are necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Black Strip area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), it is asked about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a single) for the areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save only if you move away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, we spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by non-community students, there is a further anomaly: the rent requested by foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities elect the historic halls.
Historic cinemas are closing in favor of multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth of large multi-rooms, and the death of consumption of mono-rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historical places and full of memory, "it's as if one of my friends was disappearing, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of the way and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Paradiso cinema, film that offers Tornatore the first 20 years ago, and the first Os
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: over the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have paid the most: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is at the top with 82 cinemas mono halls lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first cause of their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of ANEC, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still have to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room is closed in a city, these attendees are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation on credit for merchants: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not comply with existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to solve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono halls of historical centers and on the periphery.
The proposed regulations include tax incentives for managers and mobility benefits for the public: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking spaces and in certain parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
However, it is obvious that, to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me, has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema de Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Cinema Paradiso" which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the signs blackened by the dust.
