When energy is born from waves, now the big ones are launched.
This is an oversized deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which giants like Chevron have set their eyes, and are now trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, at the same time as the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a big boost to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore wave operating systems.
That would be twice as much as nuclear power plants produce.
And in addition, there would be the currents and tides..
Colossians at the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an installation in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it would have been a real revolutionary step.
Two years on, more and more candidates among these companies dedicated to traditional energy have always been relying on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesman for a U.S. oil giant company told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that it is precisely in Alaska that the U.S. continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for further excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which travel the energy path from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not known, according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, apart from the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears of environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the sludge up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
At the moment, we have four systems of this kind in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Green Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a mall and parking lot using six marine turbines from the East River in New York.
The movement of the water during the tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant announced that it has a long list of customers awaiting the necessary permissions to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Research of Electrical Energy, deserves at this time, the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, with others, look to the coasts, have invested $7 and a half million in 2008 and foreseen investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
